songs.

23:05.651 --> 23:11.090 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, first: For years, Common
Core academic
standards for math and English
have been the

23:11.123 --> 23:13.626 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
subject of battles all over the
country.

23:13.659 --> 23:18.931 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But there's also a move afoot to
set new standards
for science as well, and a
number of states

23:18.964 --> 23:22.201 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are starting to adopt them
voluntarily.

23:22.234 --> 23:26.272 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Special correspondent John
Tulenko of Education
Week reports.

23:26.305 --> 23:34.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: It takes just 10
minutes to
cross through Gillette, Wyoming.
This small

23:34.246 --> 23:41.320 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
city sits in the northeast
corner of the state,
surrounded by hundreds of miles
of prairie.

23:41.353 --> 23:47.559 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But schools here in Campbell
County are on
the edge of something big, the
next generation

23:47.593 --> 23:49.461 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
science standards.

23:49.495 --> 23:50.929 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTY MATHES, Sage Valley
Junior High School:
You are going to build a strand
of DNA, and

23:50.963 --> 23:54.967 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
you are going to decode it and
figure out
what that DNA actually says.

23:55.000 --> 24:00.005 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: For Christy Mathes
at Sage Valley
Junior High School, the new
standards are

24:00.039 --> 24:02.207 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
about learning to think like a
scientist.

24:02.241 --> 24:06.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTY MATHES: There's a lot of
really good
stuff in them. Every standard is
a performance

24:06.945 --> 24:12.051 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
task. It's not, the child needs
to memorize
these things. It's the student
needs to be

24:12.084 --> 24:18.057 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to do some pretty intense
stuff. We are
analyzing, we are critiquing, we
are creating,

24:18.090 --> 24:21.060 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
we are actually doing the
science.

24:21.093 --> 24:27.266 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Take today's
lesson on genes.
Mathes had her students pick
fictional character

24:27.299 --> 24:32.204 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
cards with the name, height,
hair and eye
color of each character.

24:32.237 --> 24:37.276 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
CHRISTY MATHES: This is a
secret. Just you
and your group know.

24:37.309 --> 24:43.282 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: In teams, they
built a genetic
model of their character's
traits and then

24:43.315 --> 24:45.017 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
the groups traded models.

24:45.050 --> 24:49.722 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTY MATHES: And then they're
going to
figure out who you had based on
what you code

24:49.755 --> 24:50.956 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
for.

24:50.989 --> 24:54.293 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: OK, so orange,
red, red represents
what?

24:54.326 --> 24:56.795 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
STUDENT: She has blue eyes.

24:56.829 --> 24:58.797 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
JOHN TULENKO: Blue eyes.

24:58.831 --> 25:03.235 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
What did you grasp about
genetics from doing
this exercise today?

25:03.268 --> 25:07.473 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STUDENT: That there are so
different many
parts of genetics that go into
so many different

25:07.506 --> 25:12.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
things. Something as small as
like the size
of a gene, it's really, really
small. It can

25:12.411 --> 25:14.880 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
change drastically how your life
turns out.

25:14.913 --> 25:19.885 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Developed by the
National Academy
of Sciences and others, the next
generation

25:19.918 --> 25:23.222 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
standards are more comprehensive
than what
teachers here had been using.

25:23.255 --> 25:25.290 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MAHONEY, Sage Valley
Junior High School:
You might have had a teacher
that liked a

25:25.324 --> 25:29.128 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dinosaur unit, and they threw it
out in the
2nd grade, and then the same
unit get taught

25:29.161 --> 25:32.131 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the 3rd grade and in the 4th
grade, and
you're like, well, I know a lot
about dinosaurs.

25:32.164 --> 25:37.069 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Before the new
standards, middle
school teachers like Mike
Mahoney were left

25:37.102 --> 25:38.871 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
to fill the gaps.

25:38.904 --> 25:42.674 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
MICHAEL MAHONEY: I would always
have to start
at the -- like nobody knew
anything, at the

25:42.708 --> 25:48.747 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
very beginning: What is science?
And it's
kind of tough to get into a lot
of the different

25:48.781 --> 25:52.184 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
curriculum things that you want
to teach when
you have to spend so much time
just on the

25:52.217 --> 25:53.952 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
basics.

25:53.986 --> 25:57.256 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: The new standards
brought more
structure, spelling out for the
first time

25:57.289 --> 26:00.426 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
what should be taught, grade by
grade, in
elementary school.

26:00.459 --> 26:05.497 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
CHRISTY MATHES: Every 5th grader
is going
to have this experience. Every
4th grader

26:05.531 --> 26:10.769 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
is going to have this
experience. Then those
kids come to junior high and
it's not a catch-up

26:10.803 --> 26:15.174 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
game. You know, what did you
miss? What did
you get? What do I need to do?
They are always

26:15.207 --> 26:18.177 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
building on what came before and
what comes
next.

26:18.210 --> 26:22.848 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: In Wyoming,
Campbell County
is leading the way with these
standards, which

26:22.881 --> 26:27.986 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the state has yet to adopt
officially; 17
other states are already on
board, accounting

26:28.020 --> 26:34.593 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
for an estimated 35 percent of
public school
students nationwide.

26:34.626 --> 26:37.396 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
David Evans heads the National
Association
of Science Teachers.

26:37.429 --> 26:39.198 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EVANS, Executive Director,
National
Association of Science Teachers:
I think that

26:39.231 --> 26:44.303 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the most important reason for
developing new
standards is that we have
actually learned

26:44.336 --> 26:51.944 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot about the way children
learn. And children
learn science best by actually
doing it.

26:51.977 --> 26:56.448 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: So far, there's
been little
pushback. Unlike the Common
Core, there aren't

26:56.482 --> 27:01.053 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
yet state-level science tests to
hold schools
and teachers accountable, and
the federal

27:01.086 --> 27:02.788 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
role has been different too.

27:02.821 --> 27:06.725 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID EVANS: The federal
government and the
Department of Education really
hasn't had

27:06.758 --> 27:11.663 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
anything to do with the next
generation science
standards. It's really just that
simple. There

27:11.697 --> 27:14.166 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
have not been strong incentives
and there
hasn't been any arm-twisting.

27:14.199 --> 27:17.903 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: But these new
standards still
have a long way to go.

27:17.936 --> 27:23.008 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
DAVID EVANS: There's an
established line of
data right now that documents
the fact that

27:23.041 --> 27:27.145 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
we're not spending very much
time teaching
science in elementary school.

27:27.179 --> 27:33.185 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Nationwide,
schools spend 143
minutes a day on math and
reading, but only

27:33.218 --> 27:36.221 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
20 minutes on science. And
there's another
big concern.

27:36.255 --> 27:42.160 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EVANS: The majority of
elementary school
teachers don't feel comfortable
teaching science.

27:42.194 --> 27:47.032 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Most elementary school teachers
don't receive
a lot of preparation in science
itself or

27:47.065 --> 27:48.600 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in science education.

27:48.634 --> 27:51.436 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
WOMAN: So how does the light
travel?

27:51.470 --> 27:55.874 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: To help its
teachers, Campbell
County is using a federal grant
worth just

27:55.908 --> 27:59.745 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
under a million dollars to
develop new lessons
for every grade.

27:59.778 --> 28:01.513 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Jamie Howe teaches 4th grade.

28:01.547 --> 28:09.555 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JAMIE HOWE, Teacher: I have
learned to step
back and let their exploration
take over.

28:09.588 --> 28:14.493 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, before, you know, you would
always want
to help them and guide them and
tell them

28:14.526 --> 28:20.766 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
