language that had emphasized the
major role

30:06.972 --> 30:12.778 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of human activities, such as
fossil fuel combustion,
when teaching students about the
causes of

30:12.811 --> 30:14.813 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
global warming.

30:14.846 --> 30:21.820 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID EVANS: Changing the
standards to prevent
teachers from teaching what is
clearly scientifically

30:21.853 --> 30:26.992 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
accepted documented information
is unfortunate.

30:27.025 --> 30:31.930 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But the practices of science and
the way that
science is done and teaching
students to be

30:31.963 --> 30:37.369 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
able to go out and ask their own
questions,
collect the evidence, and know
how to engage

30:37.402 --> 30:40.539 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
in a scientific argument is very
encouraging.

30:40.572 --> 30:46.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JOHN TULENKO: Today, Wyoming has
put its modified
standards out for public review.
They could

30:46.078 --> 30:50.215 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
make it to the governor's desk
for approval
by late fall.

30:50.248 --> 30:58.156 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In Campbell County, Wyoming, I'm
John Tulenko
of Education Week, reporting for
the "PBS

30:58.190 --> 31:01.426 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
NewsHour."

31:01.460 --> 31:14.573 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: The fall in world
oil prices has
likely hit no country as hard as
it has Venezuela.

31:14.606 --> 31:20.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Once flush with cash, the
country is now in
crisis, with a collapsing
economy, skyrocketing

31:20.946 --> 31:26.551 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
crime and inflation rates, and
major food
shortages, all this as the
government of President

31:26.585 --> 31:30.188 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Nicolas Maduro tries to maintain
control.

31:30.222 --> 31:35.026 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For more on this situation, we
turn to Nicholas
Casey of The New York Times, who
is reporting

31:35.060 --> 31:36.561 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
tonight from Caracas.

31:36.595 --> 31:38.396 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
Thank you for joining us.

31:38.430 --> 31:43.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, Nicholas, give me a sense
about how long
this collapse -- it feels like a
slow-motion

31:43.135 --> 31:46.371 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
collapse -- how long has it been
going on
and what has caused it?

31:46.404 --> 31:49.641 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS CASEY, The New York
Times: It's been
going on for a couple of years
now.

31:49.674 --> 31:54.946 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's been tied to the
collapse in oil
prices in Venezuela. Venezuela
gets almost

31:54.980 --> 31:59.751 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
all of its revenue from oil. So,
when these
prices started to collapse, the
first thing

31:59.785 --> 32:05.457 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you saw was that some of the
foods started
to disappear, not in huge
quantities, but

32:05.490 --> 32:09.127 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
enough that there were lines in
front of stores.

32:09.161 --> 32:14.099 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The electricity started to
disappear. There's
even problems with water right
now because

32:14.132 --> 32:18.470 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the government doesn't have the
money that
it needs. Now, what's happened
with the food

32:18.503 --> 32:22.808 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is that there has been so much
which has gone
at this point, that people are
starting to

32:22.841 --> 32:24.609 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
get hungry.

32:24.643 --> 32:30.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And last week and the week
before, we saw
a wave of lootings of stores.
People basically

32:30.048 --> 32:34.920 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
left these lines that they were
gathered in
and started to go directly into
the stores,

32:34.953 --> 32:37.088 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
break down the doors, and take
things that
were inside.

32:37.122 --> 32:43.395 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You say that the
lack -- the collapse
of the oil -- of oil prices
contributed to

32:43.428 --> 32:51.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this. How much was that tied up
with the collapse
in faith of this current
leadership, of President

32:51.136 --> 32:54.306 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Maduro? How much of one thing
creating the
other?

32:54.339 --> 32:59.845 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS CASEY: Well, it's not
just, as you
point out, the collapse of the
oil prices

32:59.878 --> 33:02.781 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
which has caused what's happened
here.

33:02.814 --> 33:07.219 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
There are other countries, like
Mexico and
Brazil, which have a lot of oil
revenues themselves,

33:07.252 --> 33:14.092 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and don't have the same problems
as Venezuela.
Venezuela and Maduro came after
years of what

33:14.125 --> 33:19.664 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a lot of economists say was
economic mismanagement
by Hugo Chavez, who totally
transformed the

33:19.698 --> 33:21.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
economy here.

33:21.499 --> 33:26.004 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government spent lots of
money, lots of
money, and didn't save much for
a time when

33:26.037 --> 33:31.209 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
the price of oil wouldn't be as
high as it
was before. So, now Venezuela
finds itself

33:31.243 --> 33:36.414 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
in the position where it needs
money. It doesn't
produce a lot of food. It needs
money to import

33:36.448 --> 33:38.750 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
food, and it doesn't have
anything right now.

33:38.783 --> 33:43.955 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, in the short term, it's the
price of oil
which has got us here. But in
the long term,

33:43.989 --> 33:48.727 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's a lot of economic changes
that took place
in this country in the so-called
Bolivarian

33:48.760 --> 33:51.229 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Revolution that came from Hugo
Chavez.

33:51.263 --> 33:55.901 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
GWEN IFILL: So, you are
witnessing food riots;
you are witnessing a lot of
economic angst

33:55.934 --> 34:02.707 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
as well. Is there also hoarding
going on,
people who are just --
businesses or individual

34:02.741 --> 34:04.910 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
merchants who are just keeping
it to themselves?

34:04.943 --> 34:10.015 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS CASEY: Well, that's one
thing that
the government is blaming on
what's happening.

34:10.048 --> 34:15.287 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Personally, as a reporter, I
have not seen
people have been able to hoard
large amounts

34:15.320 --> 34:21.760 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of food, because there's not a
lot of food
to find. The idea of being able
to hoard eggs

34:21.793 --> 34:26.698 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
or sugar or rice seems almost
impossible,
given the amounts of these
things that are

34:26.731 --> 34:28.433 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
arriving.

34:28.466 --> 34:30.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And even on an individual level,
there's a
lot of people who would love to
be able to

34:30.936 --> 34:36.441 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have a stash for the event that
they couldn't
get any more, but most people
are just thinking

34:36.474 --> 34:38.610 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
of day to day, what they're able
to get.

34:38.643 --> 34:42.814 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Are there any
efforts under way
by international organizations,
like Organization

34:42.847 --> 34:45.817 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of American States, to try to
intervene, to
try to help?

34:45.850 --> 34:50.322 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
NICHOLAS CASEY: Well, yes, the
OAS is trying
to put pressure now on
Venezuela.

34:50.355 --> 34:56.661 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And it's more political pressure
right now.
There is an effort under way to
recall President

34:56.695 --> 35:02.667 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nicolas Maduro, largely because
of all these
economic problems which the
country is having.

35:02.701 --> 35:07.038 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The government seems to be
trying to slow
the process down, or at least
fight it.

35:07.072 --> 35:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And what's happened now is that
the Organization
of American States is holding a
special meeting

35:12.610 --> 35:18.516 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this week to try to determine
whether Venezuela
is in violation of its
democratic charter.

35:18.550 --> 35:24.289 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, this could eventually
result in Venezuela
being kicked out of the OAS,
which is kind

35:24.322 --> 35:30.228 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of like a U.N. sort of body that
is in the
Western Hemisphere.

35:30.261 --> 35:35.100 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
This would be an embarrassment
for Venezuela.
But in terms of changing the
situation with

35:35.133 --> 35:41.339 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
how much food is here, that
doesn't get Venezuelans
very far. They're not going to
see suddenly

35:41.373 --> 35:46.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
their eggs and rice on the
shelves because
of the political pressure that's
going on

35:46.978 --> 35:49.481 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
against Venezuela from the
international community.

35:49.514 --> 35:53.284 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: You wrote in one of
your stories
that eggs used to be used for
celebration,

35:53.318 --> 35:55.553 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
but now an egg is like gold.

35:55.587 --> 35:58.590 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Nicholas Casey of The New York
Times, thank
you for your reporting from
Caracas.

35:58.623 --> 36:04.963 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
NICHOLAS CASEY: Thanks for
having me.

36:04.996 --> 36:13.505 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
GWEN IFILL: Now to our series on
Broken Justice.

36:13.538 --> 36:18.510 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, we look at a part of
the criminal
justice system that tends to get
less attention,

36:18.543 --> 36:20.378 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
prisoners with disabilities.

36:20.412 --> 36:22.480 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
Judy recorded this conversation
yesterday.

36:22.514 --> 36:27.919 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: A new report
breaks down public
data to outline the scope of the
issue.

36:27.952 --> 36:34.759 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It says more than 750,000 people
with disabilities
are behind bars in the U.S.,
including more

36:34.793 --> 36:42.133 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
than half-a-million with
cognitive impairments,
at least 250,000 with mobility
problems, and

36:42.167 --> 36:46.271 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
140,000 who are blind or have
vision loss.

36:46.304 --> 36:51.876 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The report was issued by a
nonprofit disability
group known as RespectAbility,
which also

36:51.910 --> 36:57.248 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hopes to cast a spotlight on
what happens
to individuals after they leave
prison.

36:57.282 --> 37:02.554 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Jennifer Laszlo Mizrahi is the
president and
CEO of this group, and she joins
me now.

37:02.587 --> 37:04.289 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
Welcome to the program.

37:04.322 --> 37:05.557 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI,
President and CEO,
RespectAbility: Thank you for
having me.

37:05.590 --> 37:07.425 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Why was this
important for
you to focus on?

37:07.459 --> 37:11.496 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: Well,
this was a
great injustice, because what
you predominantly

37:11.529 --> 37:16.868 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
see are individuals of color,
people who are
African-Americans, Hispanic, new
immigrants,

37:16.901 --> 37:21.005 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
whose disabilities were never
appropriately
diagnosed or addressed.

37:21.039 --> 37:25.276 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I myself am somebody with a
disability. And
so I know it can be harder to
get ahead, but

37:25.310 --> 37:31.182 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
if you are doubly disadvantaged,
if you have
multiple minority status, the
school-to-prison

37:31.216 --> 37:33.351 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
pipeline is almost a direct
ticket.

37:33.384 --> 37:37.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: I know I was just
looking at
some census data this afternoon.
People with

37:37.188 --> 37:40.925 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
disabilities make up something
like 19, 20
percent of population overall.

37:40.959 --> 37:46.564 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But your report finds they are
over 30 percent
of people behind bars in this
country. How

37:46.598 --> 37:48.466 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
did that happen?

37:48.500 --> 37:52.370 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: It
really happens
when young people who have
dyslexia or executive

37:52.403 --> 37:57.642 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
function disorder don't get the
diagnosis,
don't get the accommodations
that they need

37:57.675 --> 37:59.577 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
and they deserve in school.

37:59.611 --> 38:04.482 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They wind up getting in trouble,
getting suspended,
dropping out of school. They're
not graduating

38:04.516 --> 38:08.419 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
high school and they're getting
in trouble
very early. So you can really
see the problem

38:08.453 --> 38:13.625 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
only -- already almost predict
the outcome
when somebody is in the third
grade, if these

38:13.658 --> 38:15.160 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
issues are not addressed.

38:15.193 --> 38:18.596 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Is one of your
arguments that
they were wrongly convicted?

38:18.630 --> 38:23.101 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: In some
cases, yes,
because, in some cases, what has
happened

38:23.134 --> 38:28.106 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
is they have an intellectual
disability that
they don't understand the
charges that are

38:28.139 --> 38:33.411 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
against them, and they have not
gotten the
legal -- the legal support that
they need.

38:33.444 --> 38:37.382 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And, in some cases, they're
very, very smart,
and they might be deaf. There's
all kinds

38:37.415 --> 38:42.987 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of situation where individuals
who are hearing-impaired
are not given the right language
supports

38:43.021 --> 38:46.124 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
with ASL, American Sign
Language, so they
can defend themselves.

38:46.157 --> 38:50.161 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, we have real injustice for
people who
are in jail, and there are
people who committed

38:50.195 --> 38:53.464 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
crimes because their path to
success wasn't
in place.

38:53.498 --> 38:58.570 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: To what extent
are our jails,
our city jails, county jails,
and state and

38:58.603 --> 39:02.373 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
federal prisons equipped to deal
with these
issues?

39:02.407 --> 39:05.777 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: They
are not even
remotely equipped to deal. And
most of it

39:05.810 --> 39:08.880 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
is not equipment. It's actually
training.
It's awareness.

39:08.913 --> 39:14.252 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
For example, somebody who lived
in a house
with lead paint poisoning,
somebody like Freddie

39:14.285 --> 39:18.923 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Gray, who is a case we're all
familiar with,
he didn't have the ability to
follow multistep

39:18.957 --> 39:20.992 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
instructions.

39:21.025 --> 39:25.296 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so, in school, people
thought he had behavior
differences, when it was really
learning differences.

39:25.330 --> 39:28.933 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And so he was suspended, and
then he didn't
complete school, and then he was
in and out

39:28.967 --> 39:30.702 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
of the correction system.

39:30.735 --> 39:35.039 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then when somebody like that
goes into
incarceration, again, lots of
complicated

39:35.073 --> 39:38.076 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
instructions, and before you
know it, they're
in solitary confinement.

39:38.109 --> 39:45.617 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: To what extent
are either legislators,
are federal -- are the Congress
looking at

39:45.650 --> 39:51.656 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this issue, addressing it? You
and I were
just speaking about efforts
right now to look

39:51.689 --> 39:55.660 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
at prison reform. But you were
saying disabilities
are not a part of that.

39:55.693 --> 39:58.429 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI:
Unfortunately, the
data just has not been known.

39:58.463 --> 40:03.735 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It's sort of like the housing
crisis, where
all the data was sitting there
hidden in plain

40:03.768 --> 40:08.606 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
sight, but nobody was looking at
it. It's
really this explosive bomb of
information

40:08.640 --> 40:10.475 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
that no one was looking at.

40:10.508 --> 40:14.912 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So the new legislation that is
being proposed
does not address any of these
issues at all.

40:14.946 --> 40:20.985 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
By the way, I do support these
prison reforms.
There are people who really
shouldn't be in

40:21.019 --> 40:25.690 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
the prison system because of
their long sentences
for nonviolent offenses.

40:25.723 --> 40:30.328 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But you have got to have a
pathway to get
a job, because the way things
are now, these

40:30.361 --> 40:36.167 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
individuals who leave
incarceration, they're
not literate, and they wind up
back in prison.

40:36.200 --> 40:40.638 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: And it is -- as
we said a moment,
it is part of the focus of this
report, what

40:40.672 --> 40:45.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:80% size:87.5%
these individuals with
disabilities face once,
if and when they are released.

40:45.376 --> 40:47.312 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: Right.

40:47.345 --> 40:51.449 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
What you see is that
three-quarters of individuals
who are released from
incarceration -- and,

40:51.482 --> 40:56.988 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
by the way, that's 600,000
people every single
year -- within five years,
three-quarters

40:57.021 --> 41:01.626 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
of them are back in jail. The
system is broken,
and it absolutely must be fixed.

41:01.659 --> 41:05.863 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How -- Jennifer
Mizrahi, how
do you -- how do you even begin
to get your

41:05.897 --> 41:12.270 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
arms around this? What are some
steps that
you argue need to be taken
immediately and

41:12.303 --> 41:14.172 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
in the near term?

41:14.205 --> 41:17.342 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: Well,
in terms of
thinking about when people
reenter the community,

41:17.375 --> 41:22.213 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
you need to be ready to have
scaffolding for
success, so that people can get
a job, so

41:22.246 --> 41:24.215 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
that they can get their
medication.

41:24.248 --> 41:29.787 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
People with significant mental
health differences
who need medication to keep from
having psychotic

41:29.821 --> 41:34.659 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
episodes leave incarceration
with no health
care, and therefore no medicine,
and then

41:34.692 --> 41:38.763 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
it's not surprising that they're
doing something
that's putting them back in
jail.

41:38.796 --> 41:42.867 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So there's basic things on the
exit. There's
things you need to do for
accommodations while

41:42.900 --> 41:48.506 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
they're incarcerated, especially
around literacy
and training, to help them build
those skills.

41:48.539 --> 41:53.378 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And then there is to ensure that
the prison
pipeline doesn't continue,
starting really

41:53.411 --> 41:58.282 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
very much with early
intervention, particularly
in minority communities, to make
sure they're

41:58.316 --> 42:00.518 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
getting the tools that they need
to succeed.

42:00.551 --> 42:04.155 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: How should people
think -- I
know there's been a lot of, of
course, publicity

42:04.188 --> 42:09.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
about crimes of all sort that
get attention
in the news media all the time.
Public -- people

42:09.627 --> 42:11.896 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
read about it and they hear
about it.

42:11.929 --> 42:17.902 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
How do they understand and weigh
the difference
between a disability that is
causing someone

42:17.935 --> 42:26.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
to do something to commit a
crime, and one
that where there's will involved
and a disability,

42:26.611 --> 42:31.149 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
and it's something for which one
has to serve
time, must be held accountable?

42:31.182 --> 42:35.486 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
JENNIFER LASZLO MIZRAHI: Well, a
crime clearly
is something that harms another
person. And

42:35.520 --> 42:40.658 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
so if you're harming people,
then there has
to be something to be done.

42:40.691 --> 42:45.530 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Now, in many cases, you can go
to a mental
health treatment program or an
addiction program

42:45.563 --> 42:51.269 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
or a work program. The
alternative sentencing
is really important, because
America has only

42:51.302 --> 42:57.041 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
5 percent of the world's
population, but we
have 25 percent of the world's
incarcerated

